reathing control during pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased central chemoreceptor sensitivity to carbon dioxide","Decreased peripheral chemoreceptor sensitivity to oxygen","Reduced brainstem respiratory centre activity","Inhibition of intercostal muscle function","Suppression of carotid body responses"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring pregnancy, progesterone causes \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased central chemoreceptor sensitivity to carbon dioxide\u003C/strong\u003E. This leads to enhanced respiratory drive and a mild chronic respiratory alkalosis, which is a normal physiological adaptation of pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased peripheral chemoreceptor sensitivity to oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E - Peripheral chemoreceptor function is maintained during pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced brainstem respiratory centre activity\u003C/strong\u003E - Respiratory centre activity is actually enhanced during pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of intercostal muscle function\u003C/strong\u003E - Respiratory muscles maintain normal function despite mechanical changes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppression of carotid body responses\u003C/strong\u003E - Carotid body function remains intact during pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe increased ventilatory drive helps meet the enhanced metabolic demands of pregnancy and facilitates carbon dioxide transfer across the placenta.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Progesterone increases respiratory drive by enhancing central chemoreceptor sensitivity to carbon dioxide during pregnancy.","The increased respiratory drive 